---
// The review-crew page: plain-language orientation for the book's readers.
export const prerender = false;
import Layout from '../../../layouts/ForeverPromiseLayout.astro';
---
<Layout title="How this review copy works" kind="howto">
  <header>
    <p class="fp-eyebrow">For the Review Crew</p>
    <h1 class="fp-title">How this review copy works</h1>
  </header>
  <article class="fp-body fp-howto-body">
    <p>Welcome. What you are holding is the complete advance draft of <em>The Forever Promise</em> —
    every chapter, the witness stations and interludes, the Muster, the Coda, and the three appendices —
    set as a private reading room. It is not public: no search engine can see it, nothing on the
    website links to it, and only people given the passcode can open it.</p>

    <h2>Reading</h2>
    <p>Start anywhere. The <a href="/writing/forever-promise/">contents page</a> lists everything in
    reading order, and every page ends with a link to the next. Each page notes its reading time.
    Notes appear at the bottom of each page, numbered afresh on every page.</p>

    <h2>The pictures</h2>
    <p>The book's photographs, maps, and drawings are still arriving. Where a picture will stand, you
    will see a labeled panel describing it; each panel links to a page about that figure — what it will
    show, where it appears, and where things stand. The <a href="/writing/forever-promise/figures/">figures
    page</a> lists the whole program. As each image lands it will appear in place, and the words around
    it will not move.</p>

    <h2>Suggesting a change</h2>
    <p>This is the important part, and it was built to take less effort than a pencil in a margin:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>On a chapter page, choose <strong>Review notes</strong> in the top bar. Then rest your cursor on
      any paragraph (on a phone or tablet, look for the small <span class="pencil">✎</span> at the end)
      and a pencil appears. Choose <strong>Review notes</strong> again whenever you want a clean reading view.</li>
      <li>Tap the pencil, write what you would change — a word, a sentence, a worry, a memory the
      passage stirred that belongs in the book — and add your name.</li>
      <li>Press send. That is all.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>For thoughts about a whole chapter — its order, its tone, something it leaves out — every page
    has a note box at the bottom.</p>

    <h2>What happens to your suggestions</h2>
    <p>Every suggestion goes straight to the writing crew's desk, attached to the exact paragraph you
    marked. The crew gathers them, weighs them, and folds them into the next draft — and nothing
    changes in this book without the authors. You cannot break anything, you cannot mark too much,
    and no suggestion is too small. If a sentence made you stumble, that stumble is exactly what this
    copy exists to catch.</p>

    <h2>One request</h2>
    <p>Please treat this copy as the private thing it is — an accounting still being checked. The
    passcode is yours to use, not to pass on; when the book is ready for the world, it will go to the
    world properly.</p>

    <p class="fp-howto-close"><em>Thank you for standing this watch with us.</em></p>
  </article>
  <p class="fp-back"><a href="/writing/forever-promise/">← To the contents page</a></p>
</Layout>

<style>
  .fp-howto-body h2 { margin-top: 1.8em; }
  .fp-howto-body ul { padding-left: 1.4rem; }
  .fp-howto-body li { margin-bottom: 0.6em; }
  .pencil { color: var(--fp-gold); }
  .fp-howto-close { margin-top: 2rem; }
  .fp-back { margin-top: 2rem; font-family: var(--fp-sans); font-size: 0.85rem; }
  .fp-back a { color: var(--fp-navy); }
</style>
